'''Diana M. Zuckerman''' (born 16 June 1950<ref>http://authorities.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?AuthRecID=3305166&v1=1&HC=1&SEQ=20071211042258&PID=27945 {{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}</ref>) is an [[Americans|American]] health policy analyst who focuses on the implications of policies for public health and patients’ health. She is an expert on national health policy, particularly in [[women's health]] and the safety and effectiveness of medical products. She is the President of the [[National Center for Health Research]] (formerly National Research Center for Women & Families) and [[the Cancer Prevention and Treatment Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stopcancerfund.org/|title=Stop Cancer Fund - Information you can use. A voice you can trust.|work=stopcancerfund.org|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Zuckerman earned her B.A. in [[psychology]] from [[Smith College]] and then obtained a [[Ph.D]] in [[psychology]] from [[THE Ohio State University|The Ohio State University]] in 1977. At [[Yale Medical School]] she was a post-doctoral fellow in [[epidemiology]] and [[public health]] from 1979 to 1980.

==Career==
She was on the faculty at [[Vassar College]] and [[Yale University]], and directed a longitudinal study of college students as director of the Seven College Study at [[Harvard University]], publishing books and articles on the impact of media on children, the impact of religion on the health of the elderly, and how women's life experiences influence their mental and physical health. She left academia in 1983 when she was selected as a Fellow in the American Association for the Advancement of Science Congressional Science Fellowship program.<ref name=center4research>[http://www.center4research.org/about-us/key-staff/ National Research Center for Women & Families staff listing] Retrieved June 14, 2010.</ref>

From 1985 to 1993 she worked at the [[U.S. Congress]] in a House subcommittee where she was responsible for a dozen Congressional oversight investigations on health and social policy, including political manipulation of government grants to prevent [[child abuse]], lack of safeguards for [[infertility treatment]]s, financial conflicts of interest among [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH) grant recipients, and the lack of safety studies on [[breast implant]]s. Information from the hearings received widespread public health, government, and media attention, resulting in several policy and regulatory changes, including the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) requiring implant manufacturers to submit safety studies for the first time.<ref name=center4research/>

In 1993, Zuckerman joined the staff of the [[Senate Veterans Affairs Committee]] and began an investigation that resulted in the first Congressional hearings focused on the possible causes of [[Gulf War syndrome]]. In 1995 she was a senior policy advisor in the [[Clinton Administration]]. From 1996, she undertook leading roles in [[non-profit organization]]s, including, from 1999, presidency of the National Research Center for Women & Families<ref name=center4research/> (renamed the [[National Center for Health Research]] in 2014) and [[The Cancer Prevention and Treatment Fund]]. In 2010, she was inducted into the Women in Medicine International Hall of Fame by the American Medical Women's Association.

Her work focuses on improving the quality of [[medical product]]s and healthcare in the United States. She has been highly critical of scientific and medical research paid for by companies, who then use this to promote their products, as well as the lack of media coverage on independently funded research that challenges industry-funded research. She has said:
:You've heard of junk science &mdash; a term coined by corporations to describe research they don’t like &mdash; but the real danger to public health might be called "checkbook science": research intended not to expand knowledge or to benefit humanity, but instead to sell products.<ref name=hype>Zuckerman, Diana (2002)[http://www.fair.org/extra/0209/hype-health.html Hype in health reporting]. Retrieved August 16, 2006.</ref>

In February 2011, Zuckerman and colleagues Paul Brown and Dr. [[Steven Nissen]] published a study in the peer-reviewed journal ''[[Archives of Internal Medicine]]'', which evaluated the FDA’s recalls of devices that the agency considered potentially deadly or otherwise very high risk.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Zuckerman DM, Brown P, Nissen SE|title=Medical device recalls and the FDA approval process|journal=Archives of Internal Medicine |volume=171|issue=11|pages=1006–11|date=June 2011|pmid=21321283|doi=10.1001/archinternmed.2011.30}}</ref> Based on FDA data, the authors determined that most of the devices that were high-risk recalls had never been studied in [[clinical trials]] prior to FDA approval, and that the FDA needed to use more stringent criteria for implanted medical devices and those used to diagnose serious illnesses, and an editorial in the same issue agreed.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Redberg RF, Dhruva SS|title=Medical device recalls: get it right the first time: Comment on "Medical device recalls and the FDA approval process"|journal=Archives of Internal Medicine|volume=171 |issue=11|pages=1011–2|date=June 2011|pmid=21321286|doi=10.1001/archinternmed.2011.27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/not-enough-safety-testing-on-medical-implant-devices-studies-claim/|title=Not enough safety testing on medical implant devices, studies claim|date=September 30, 2014|work=cbsnews.com|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/medical-devices-lack-safety-evidence-study-finds-1412017201|title=Medical Devices Lack Safety Evidence, Study Finds|author=Thomas M. Burton|date=September 29, 2014|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/30/us-fda-devices-idUSKCN0HP05Z20140930|title=Studies criticize U.S. medical device approval process|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>
In April 2011, Zuckerman presented the results of the study at a hearing of the [[United States Senate Special Committee on Aging|U.S. Senate Senate Special Committee on Aging]].<ref>http://aging.senate.gov{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}</ref>

Zuckerman is the author of five books, several book chapters, and dozens of articles in medical and academic journals, and in newspapers across the country. Her policy work has resulted in news coverage on all the major TV networks, including [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[CBS]], [[NBC]], [[CNN]], [[Fox News]], public television, ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[20/20]]'', [[National Public Radio]], and in major U.S. print media such as ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/09/business/09device.html|author=Gardiner Harris|title=F.D.A. to Check Safety of Old Devices|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=April 8, 2009|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/27/health/policy/27device.html|title=Quickly Vetted, Treatment Is Offered to Patients|author=Reed Abelson|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/04/us/long-term-data-on-complications-adds-to-criticism-of-contraceptive-implant.html|author=Ronio Caryn Rabin|title=Long-Term Data on Complications Adds to Criticism of Essure Contraceptive Implant|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/08/business/knee-replacement-device-unapproved-but-used-in-surgery.html|title=Knee Replacement Device Unapproved, but Used in Surgery|author=Marshall Allen|author2=Olga Pierce|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=February 6, 2015|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/12/04/AR2005120400887.html|title=Implant Maker Fixed Samples Only|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=December 4, 2005|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/23/nation/la-na-breast-implants-20110623|title=Breast implants: FDA stands by silicone implants|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=June 23, 2011|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Boston Globe]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2013/02/19/hip-implants-bit-more-likely-fail-women/0TTTL3ztxYQ9gyI43RR2fL/story.html|title=Hip implants a bit more likely to fail in women|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 19, 2013|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/business/globe/articles/2005/04/14/fda_panel_supports_firms_breast_implant/|title=FDA panel supports firm's breast implant|work=boston.com|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'', ''[[New York Daily News]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[U.S. News and World Report]]'', ''[[Family Circle]]'', ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'', ''[[Self (magazine)|Self]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.self.com/wellness/health/2011/01/cheap-cosmetic-surgery/|title=The True Price of Cheap Cosmetic Surgery|author=SELF Staffers|work=[[Self (magazine)|SELF]]|date=January 26, 2011|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> as well as many other newspapers, magazines, and radio programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://center4research.org/about-us/key-staff/|title=Key Staff|publisher=[[National Center for Health Research]]|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/408187_3|title=Are Breast Implants Safe?|work=[[Medscape]]|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/06/25/us/politics/ap-us-contraception-device-fda.html</ref>

===Testimonies===
Zuckerman has appeared before numerous FDA advisory committees to testify as a medical expert on a variety of drugs and devices.

On December 12, 2013, Zuckerman testified regarding the type-2 [[diabetes]] drug [[dapagliflozin]] (Farxiga), saying: "My concern about this drug is that there are just too many unanswered questions – and those unanswered questions are frightening ones. That was true when the FDA rejected this application for approval 2 years ago, and it is still true today." She cited studies that highlighted the risks that the drug poses, as well as methodological concerns such as a lack of diversity in clinical trials.<ref>http://center4research.org/public-policy/testimony-briefings-statements/statementdapagliflozin/{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}</ref>
On November 14, 2012, Zuckerman made a statement at a Capitol Hill press conference about the VALID Compounding Act. She stated that loopholes in the FDA law, including compounding pharmacies, have allowed hundreds of people to get sick with meningitis and several to die. The VALID Compounding Act is designed to close the loopholes that are so harmful to patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stopcancerfund.org/in-the-news/valid-compounding-press/|title=Statement by Dr. Diana Zuckerman, Capitol Hill Press Conference|publisher=[[The Cancer Prevention and Treatment Fund]]|date=November 14, 2012|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>

