{{Use British English|date=April 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} In [[Japan]], a person with a [[disability]] is defined as: "a person whose daily life or life in society is substantially limited over the long term due to a physical disability or mental disability".<ref name = Iwakuma >{{cite book|last=Iwakuma|first=Miho|editor-last=Kramer|editor-first=Eric Mark|title=The emerging monoculture : assimilation and the "model minority"|date=2003|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=9780275973124|chapter=Being Disabled in Modern Japan: A Minority Perspective}}</ref>{{rp|page=125}} Japan ratified the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]] (CRPD) on 20 January 2014.
==Demographics== In 1998 the government estimated that there were 5,753,000 people with disabilities in Japan, constituting about 4.8% of the total population. The totals of the three legally defined categories were: 3,170,000 [[Physical disability|physically disabled]]; 413,000 [[intellectual disability|intellectually disabled]]; and 4,170,000 have [[mental disorder|psychiatric disabilities]]. The physically disabled category was made up of people with the following impairments: 1,657,000 (56.5%) limb impairments; 305,000 (10.4%) are visually impaired; 350,000 (11.9%) have hearing impairments; while 621,000 (21.2%) had "internal disabilities" such as heart disease.<ref name = Iwakuma/>{{rp|pages=125-126}}<!-- Look for more recent statistics -->
==Legislation and government policy== {{see also|Disability rights in Japan}} Japan signed the CRPD in September 2007, but took until January 2014 to ratify it. The long delay was due to various legislative amendments and policy reforms that had to be in place before ratification.<ref name=Mayumi>{{cite web|first=Shirasawa |last=Mayumi |url=http://www.nippon.com/en/currents/d00133/ |title=The Long Road to Disability Rights in Japan |publisher=Nippon.com |date=2014-10-02 |accessdate=2016-02-29}}</ref> <!-- Commenting out empty sections ==Advocacy== ==Employment== ==Social services== ==Education== Please unhide them once content has been added -->
==Sport== [[File:2014_IWRF_World_Championship_Japan.jpg|thumb|2014 IWRF World Championship.]] [[Japan]] made its [[Paralympic]] debut by hosting the [[1964 Summer Paralympics|1964 Games]] in [[Tokyo]]. The country has participated in every subsequent edition of the [[Summer Paralympics]],<ref name=Mackay>{{cite news|last=Mackay |first=Duncan |url=http://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1028374/major-initiative-launched-to-help-japanese-athletes-prepare-for-tokyo-2020-paralympics |title=Major initiative launched to help Japanese athletes prepare for Tokyo 2020 Paralympics |publisher=Insidethegames.biz |date=2015-06-30 |accessdate=2016-02-29}}</ref> and in every edition of the [[Winter Paralympics]] since [[1976 Winter Paralympics|the first in 1976]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/sites/default/files/document/140226212841502_Japan.pdf |title=Japan - 7 facts on the Sochi 2014 Paralympics |publisher=Paralympic.org |format=PDF |accessdate=2016-02-29}}</ref> It has hosted the Paralympic Games twice, with Tokyo hosting the 1964 Summer Games, and [[Nagano, Nagano|Nagano]] the [[1998 Winter Paralympics]]. Tokyo is scheduled to host the Summer Games again in 2020.<ref name=Mackay />
